  "text": "In previous works, we used MoCap to carry out experiments aimed at analyzing relationships between body movements and other musical features in instrumental musical performance [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . For real-time musical applications, we preferred the use of various wearable sensors because they are easier to transport and use in performance situations. Optical MoCap, on the other hand, is definitely more demanding in terms of portability and setup time. As we will show more in detail, the raw data returned by wearable sensors are intrinsically different from that of MoCap, and this presents some implications for how the data are eventually interpreted and applied. Understanding how to extract meaningful descriptors from such sensors is useful beyond the domain of musical practice because similar technologies are becoming ubiquitous, employed in everyday objects such as mobile devices and game controllers.",
